=== RAW MODEL ANSWER ===
Answer: Step 1: 4-methylbenzonitrile → 4-(bromomethyl)benzonitrile by benzylic bromination (e.g. NBS, AIBN). | Step 2: 4-(bromomethyl)benzonitrile → (4-cyanobenzyl)triphenylphosphonium bromide with PPh3. | Step 3: Wittig olefination of this phosphonium salt with 2-hydroxybenzaldehyde gives 2-hydroxy-4'-cyanostilbene. | Step 4: Hydrogenation of the C=C (H2, Pd/C) affords 4-(2-hydroxybenzyl)benzonitrile. | Step 5: Controlled hydration of the nitrile gives 4-(2-hydroxybenzyl)benzamide. | Step 6: In parallel, D-glucose → 2,3,4,6-tetra-O-acetyl-alpha-D-glucopyranosyl bromide via peracetylation then anomeric bromination. | Step 7: Koenigs-Knorr O-glycosylation of 4-(2-hydroxybenzyl)benzamide with the peracetylated glucosyl bromide (e.g. Ag2CO3/Ag2O promoter) gives 4-(2-((2,3,4,6-tetra-O-acetyl-beta-D-glucopyranosyl)oxy)benzyl)benzamide; beta selectivity arises from neighboring-group participation of the 2-acetate. | Step 8: Global deacetylation (NaOMe/MeOH, Zemplén) furnishes NC(=O)c1ccc(Cc2ccccc2O[C@@H]2O[C@H](CO)[C@@H](O)[C@H](O)[C@H]2O)cc1.

